<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Members of the House Ethics Committee, not former Speaker Jim Wright, initiated 
an attempt to strike a deal and negotiate his resignation, the Dallas Times 
Herald reported. The newspaper reported that sources who asked not to be named 
said that Ethics Committee Chairman Julian C. Dixon (D-Los Angeles) phoned Rep. 
Louis Stokes (D-Ohio), the former ethics chairman, and said that Wright's 
resignation would "spare the House a harsh and divisive confrontation." Wright 
reportedly authorized negotiations but did not approach the committee to 
discuss a deal when it convened later. Wright announced his plans to resign in 
a speech May 31. 
</P>
