<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
East German leader Erich Honecker said President Bush's proposal for a 
reduction in conventional arms in Europe is a welcome step that is in tune with 
Warsaw Pact desires for speedy negotiations, according to an interview with the 
Washington Post. However, Honecker rejected Bush's call for the Berlin Wall to 
be torn down, although he said his government wants "to humanize the border 
regime" as part of generally improving relations with Western Europe and the 
United States. The paper quoted Honecker as confirming that East German border 
guards have been ordered not to use deadly force to stop civilians who attempt 
to flee into West Germany unless the guards are threatened by the attempt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
