<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
United Mine Workers President Richard Trumka wound up a weeklong demonstration 
against Pittston Coal Group Inc. at Charleston, W. Va., by promising to broaden 
the two-month-old miners' strike. "There's no doubt in my mind that it's going 
to expand," Trumka told a rally of about 12,000 strikers and their 
sympathizers. He would not say whether he would take the strike to other parts 
of the country, such as Kentucky, where about 200 Pittston miners remain on the 
job. On the final leg of a six-day march, Trumka led supporters to the state 
Capitol, where Gov. Gaston Caperton urged a compromise in the dispute over 
wages, benefits and work rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
