<HEADLINE>
<P>
DARE PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In my opinion DARE (Drug Abuse Resistance Education) is an absolute must in 
today's society! ("DARE Survives Early Doubts: L.A. Drug Effort Takes On 
International Dimensions," Part I, May 30). I do not understand how there could 
be any objections to such a program. 
</P>
<P>
Whether or not there is actual conclusive proof of a reduction in drug use is 
not so much the issue. The fact is that through DARE we provide the "helping 
hand" our children need to guide them in making the right choices about drugs. 
It's very easy to tell a child what not to do, but what is needed is a lesson 
in how to deal with certain situations involving any kind of drug, before they 
arise. This is the responsibility that DARE has taken upon itself, and 
recognition for a job well done is long overdue. 
</P>
<P>
CLARA KIRSNER 
</P>
<P>
Culver City 
</P>
</TEXT>
